<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE ROUNDUP; PEPPERDINE BEATS THE TITANS AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Pepperdine continued its recent domination of Cal State Fullerton, beating the 
Titans, 2-1, in a nonconference baseball game Wednesday at Titan Field. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the eighth consecutive time that Pepperdine has beaten Fullerton. It 
was also the second time this season that the unranked Waves (12-10) have 
beaten the top-ranked Titans (18-5). 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton leads the all-time series, 30-26. 
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine scored single runs in the first and third and Fullerton scored its 
only run in the second. 
</P>
<P>
 The Titans had a chance in the ninth but failed to score. 
</P>
<P>
 Adam Millan walked to start the inning and was sacrificed to second by Jeremy 
Giambi. 
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine then went to reliever Mauricio Estavil, who struck out pinch-hitter 
D.C. Olsen and Tony Miranda to end the game. 
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine had a chance to open a big lead in the first when the Waves loaded 
the bases with no out on a single, a walk and a hit batter. Fullerton starter 
Chad Rolish then hit No. 4 hitter Keven Dell'Amico to force in a run.  
</P>
<P>
 Catcher Bret Hemphill helped Rolish out by picking off David Rosato at third 
for the first out. Rolish got the next two batters to end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
 The Titans scored in the second when Millan doubled to open the inning. He 
came home on a two-out error by Pepperdine first baseman David Newhan. 
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine took the lead in the third.  
</P>
<P>
 Ryan Christenson singled and went to third on a hit-and-run single by Rosato. 
Jason Cohen followed with an RBI single and Waves led, 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
 Rolish (5-2) allow two runs in seven innings and took the loss. 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton plays at UCLA at 7 p.m. Friday then play host the Bruins at 1 p.m. 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 Chapman 6, Whitman (Wash.) 0 -- Allistair Ray pitched a complete-game 
five-hitter for Chapman, striking out seven. 
</P>
<P>
 Third baseman Duke Best had a double and four RBIs for Chapman, which improves 
to 6-13. Whitman is 1-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
