<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: LONG BEACH; GUIDED MISSILE DESTROYER TO BE COMMISSIONED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Navy's newest guided missile destroyer, the $800-million Curtis Wilbur, 
has arrived in Long Beach for commissioning ceremonies Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 The warship will be the last vessel commissioned at the Long Beach Naval 
Station, which is scheduled to close Sept. 30 because of military cutbacks. 
</P>
<P>
 The ship, which was built in Maine by Bath Iron Works, is equipped with the 
Aegis Combat System that allows its crew to track more than 200 sea and air 
targets while simultaneously engaging those targets with the ship's weapons. It 
is named after Curtis Wilbur, former Navy secretary and California Supreme 
Court justice. 
</P>
<P>
 Navy Secretary John H. Dalton will be the keynote speaker during commissioning 
ceremonies, which begin at 11 a.m. The ship's home port is San Diego. 
</P>
</TEXT>
