<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: CYPRESS; CITY OKS NEW CLUB, WITH RESERVATIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A building known to local residents for having a history of troublesome 
restaurants and nightclubs will open as a new club in three months. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council granted a business and entertainment permit to Juan Garcia, 
who plans to open Los Rios Mexican Restaurant and Nightclub in the now-vacant 
building in Cinnamon Square at Ball Road and Juanita Street. 
</P>
<P>
 More than three years ago before the building failed as the Meadowlark 
restaurant, it was known as Promises, a rock 'n' roll nightclub. The club was 
shut down after residents complained of loud noise late at night and customers 
loitering in the parking lot, city officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Before Promises, several other restaurants briefly occupied the building, 
which had become known as problems among residents. 
</P>
<P>
 Because of the site's history, council members restricted Los Rios' operating 
hours from 11 a.m. to midnight Sunday through Thursday and 11 a.m. to 2 a.m. on 
the weekends and nights before holidays. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, Garcia offered to pay the city 35% of the admission he will 
charge customers on nights when the bands play. The charge will be between $10 
and $15, and Garcia said he expects to fill the place with 300 people each 
weekend night. City officials said the restaurant admission tax is the first of 
its kind in Cypress. 
</P>
<P>
 Garcia also will hire two security guards, one for inside and one for outside. 
</P>
<P>
 Nevertheless, Councilwoman Cecilia L. Age said: "I'm nervous about this 
business. It's in an area where we've had problems in the past and given the 
history of that place, we're walking on eggshells." 
</P>
<P>
 A business owner in Cinnamon Square pleaded with the City Council to allow 
Garcia to open his restaurant. "Please give small business a chance," Tim Wang 
said. "Give a small potato something to live on." 
</P>
<P>
 Council members required that the business permit be reviewed in one year. In 
addition, if residents complain about the business, the city may revoke 
Garcia's permit to provide live entertainment.MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
