<P>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL / NCAA MEN'S TOURNAMENT UPDATE; MIDWEST; SOUTHWEST TEXAS IS 
TAKING IT EASY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Southwest Texas State (25-6) is seeded 15th, has never played in the NCAA 
tournament and today faces second-seeded Massachusetts (27-6) in the first 
round at Wichita, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
 So how did the Bobcats prepare? 
</P>
<P>
 By cutting back on practice, reflecting on the past and letting the future 
take care of itself. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just want us to play as well as we can play," Coach Jim Wooldridge said. 
"Win or lose, if we do that, I think our players and myself will feel good. If 
we don't win, I want us to feel good about who we are. That's as important to 
me as anything." 
</P>
<P>
 But there's nothing laid-back about St. Louis, which last played in the NCAA 
tournament in 1957. The seventh-seeded Billikens (23-5) play 10th-seeded 
Maryland (16-11) today. 
</P>
<P>
 "Now that we've finally got a chance to play in the tournament, we're not just 
happy to be in it. We've come here to win some games," said second-year Coach 
Charlie Spoonhour, a frequent NCAA visitor with Southwest Missouri State. 
"We're going to do what it takes to win." 
</P>
