<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part E; Page 3; Column 2; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
2838 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OC HIGH / STUDENT NEWS & VIEWS; ENTERTAINING IDEAS ABOUT HAVING FUN ON A 
BUDGET? DON'T DESPAIR. WITH A SENSE OF ADVENTURE, AND MAYBE A FEW BUCKS, 
THERE'S NO NEED TO BREAK THE BANK IN ORDER TO BREAK THE ROUTINE.; ON THE CHEAP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What's there to do when you're low on bucks? Plenty, found three OC High 
correspondents who went scouting for interesting outings that didn't require a 
financial investment.  
</P>
<P>
 The correspondents -- Alison Koodrich, a senior at Ocean View High School in 
Huntington Beach; Michelle Pham, a junior at Trabuco Hills High School in 
Mission Viejo, and Amy Suarez, a senior at Troy High School in Fullerton -- 
each went their separate ways to find entertaining destinations. 
</P>
<P>
 They were looking for things to do for $10 or less -- and with only a couple 
of exceptions -- they came in on or under budget. Here are a few of the 
possibilities: 
</P>
<P>
 * Side-By-Side 
</P>
<P>
 16091 Gothard St., at Edinger Avenue Huntington Beach (714) 847-8333  
</P>
<P>
 Side-By-Side's roller-skating and ice rinks feature group or private lessons, 
figure skating, power skating, broom hockey, roller hockey and more. Admission 
to the roller rink is $4.50; skate rental is $2. Admission to the ice rink is 
$5.50, with a $2.50 charge for skate rental. 
</P>
<P>
 * Fountain Valley Family Fun Center 
</P>
<P>
 16800 Magnolia St. Fountain Valley (714) 842-1111 or (714) 842-1011  
</P>
<P>
 Choose from two miniature golf courses, 16 baseball batting cages, bumper 
boats, go-carts, arcade and Bullwinkle's Family restaurant. Costs: miniature 
golf, $5; bumper boats, $3.25; go-carts, $3.75; batting cages, $1 for 18 
pitches. 
</P>
<P>
 * Team Bicycle Rentals 
</P>
<P>
 508 Main St. Huntington Beach (714) 969-5480  
</P>
<P>
 Rent a bike and ride down Main Street for $5 an hour or $15 a day. Or rent 
roller-blades and cruise along the beach path for just $5 an hour, $13 a day.  
</P>
<P>
 * Huntington Central Park 
</P>
<P>
 On Goldenwest Street (between Slater and Talbert avenues) Huntington Beach 
Pack a picnic basket and take your friends for a relaxing day in the park. Go 
on a bike ride, take a walk through the nature center, play Frisbee golf or 
walk your dog around the lake. You can also grab a snack at Alice's Breakfast 
in the Park, 6622 Lakeview Drive, (714) 848-0690.  
</P>
<P>
 * Pacific's Hi-Way 39 Drive-In 
</P>
<P>
 7901 Trask Ave. Westminster (714) 891-3693  
</P>
<P>
 Catch a movie in your pajamas without getting out of the car. General 
admission is only $4.50 per person. Shows start at dusk nightly.  
</P>
<P>
 * Ruby's Diner 
</P>
<P>
 End of Municipal Pier in Seal Beach (310) 431-7829  
</P>
<P>
 or 
</P>
<P>
 End of Balboa Pier in Newport Beach (714) 675-7829 Take a walk down either 
pier and stop for a shake at Ruby's. Whether you sit inside or out, the only 
way to avoid the spectacular view is by closing your eyes. (You may want to sit 
inside because, quite simply, it can get really cold outside at the end of the 
pier.) And the burgers are a delight: Ruby's Burger is $3.89; the chili size 
burger is $5.64. For beach-lovers, park some distance away and roller skate or 
bike to the pier, which makes arriving seem even more worth it. Open for 
breakfast, lunch and dinner. 
</P>
<P>
 * Denim & Diamonds 
</P>
<P>
 7979 Center Ave. Huntington Beach (714) 892-4666  
</P>
<P>
 Learn to line dance by taking free country-Western dance lessons from 3 to 5 
p.m. and 6 to 8 p.m. on Sunday evenings. Put on your boots and dance up a storm 
until 8, because after that, no one under 21 is allowed. 
</P>
<P>
 * Corona del Mar Tide Pools 
</P>
<P>
 Take Pacific Coast Highway south through Corona del Mar, turn right on Poppy 
and keep going until it dead-ends at Ocean Boulevard. Park there and take the 
beach path to check out sea anemones and starfish at the tide pools. An entire 
day of adventure that's even educational. 
</P>
<P>
 * Westminster Lanes 
</P>
<P>
 6471 Westminster Blvd. Westminster (714) 893-5005  
</P>
<P>
 Take all your friends and practice bowling for $3 per game per person. Shoe 
rental is $1.75. A special feature is "Rock & Bowl," when you can bowl to rock 
music from 11:30 p.m. to 3 a.m. on Friday and Saturday nights for $8.50 per 
person. 
</P>
<P>
 * Movieland Wax Museum 
</P>
<P>
 7711 Beach Blvd. (one block north of Knott's Berry Farm) Buena Park (714) 
522-1155 Find yourself among the biggest stars of the movies and TV for only 
$12.95. Don't forget your camera! 
</P>
<P>
 * Griffith Observatory 
</P>
<P>
 2800 E. Observatory Road Los Angeles Take Interstate 5 north, exit at Los 
Feliz Boulevard. Go left at the stop sign and continue for a mile, then turn 
right on Hillhurst Avenue and follow the signs. Planetarium admission is $4. 
The Lazarium Light Shows cost $6.50 and are presented Tuesday-Sunday at 6 and 8 
p.m., with additional shows at 8:45 p.m. on Friday and Saturday evenings. For 
program information, call (818) 997-3624. 
</P>
<P>
 The telescope on the roof and the Hall of Science are free. The observatory is 
open from 2 to 10 p.m. Tuesday-Friday, 12:30 to 10 p.m. Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Super-Saver Cinema 
</P>
<P>
 12343 Seal Beach Blvd. (in the Rossmoor Shopping Center, one-quarter mile 
north of Interstate 405) (310) 594-9411 Come and see the latest movies -- the 
admission price is always $1.50. That leaves enough money for popcorn and 
candy, too! 
</P>
<P>
 * Big Shots Bar & Grill 
</P>
<P>
 23512 El Toro Road Lake Forest (714) 830-2255  
</P>
<P>
 Enjoy taking your best shot on 13 pool tables. Burgers, pizza and appetizers 
available. (They stamp your hand if your are a minor.) Hours: 11 a.m. to 2 a.m. 
daily. 
</P>
<P>
 * ARC Forest Lane 
</P>
<P>
 22771 Center Drive Lake Forest (714) 770-0055  
</P>
<P>
 Take to the alleys on one of Forest Lane's 40 bowling lanes. There also is a 
snack bar, video games and air hockey. Hours: 9 a.m. to midnight Sunday through 
Thursday; 10 a.m. to 2 a.m. Friday through Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
 * Diedrich Coffee 
</P>
<P>
 22621 Lake Forest Drive Lake Forest  
</P>
<P>
 (714) 837-4555. and other locations throughout county  
</P>
<P>
 Enjoy conversation with friends over assorted coffee drinks, pastries and 
muffins. A coffee card is available and can help cut costs -- after 10 coffee 
drinks, the 11th is free. 
</P>
<P>
 In Lake Forest: live entertainment on Fridays and Saturdays from 8 to 11 p.m. 
Shop hours: 5:30 a.m. to 11 p.m. Monday through Friday; 5:30 a.m. to midnight 
Saturday and Sunday. Hours vary from shop to shop. 
</P>
<P>
 * Batter's Up 
</P>
<P>
 29702 Avenida de las Banderas Rancho Santa Margarita (714) 589-2665  
</P>
<P>
 A variety of activities are available here: seven batting cages, Hi Ball (a 
game of basketball on a trampoline) and video games. There is a mini-sporting 
goods store, snack bar and conference room for parties and meetings. Hours: 
noon to 9 p.m. Monday through Friday; 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. weekends. 
</P>
<P>
 * Haute Cafe 
</P>
<P>
 22421 Antonio Parkway Rancho Santa Margarita (714) 459-8828  
</P>
<P>
 If you've got an opinion about something, like to tell jokes or want to share 
your poetry, take your friends to Haute Cafe, which has an open mike night on 
Thursdays. Enjoy the show over assorted coffees, desserts and muffins. Live 
entertainment -- from blues, jazz, folk and local high school bands -- is 
featured from 8 to 11 p.m. Friday and Saturday. Cafe hours: 6 a.m. to 11 p.m. 
Sunday through Thursday, 6 a.m to midnight, Friday through Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Bodacious Buns 
</P>
<P>
 31431 Santa Margarita Parkway Rancho Santa Margarita (714) 459-0300  
</P>
<P>
 This gathering place overlooks Rancho Santa Margarita Lake, so it's an 
enjoyable spot to spend some time over gourmet coffee, cinnamon rolls, muffins, 
sandwiches and soup. It opened around Thanksgiving, and the owners plan to have 
live music soon. Hours: 6 a.m. to 8 p.m. Sunday through Thursday; 6 a.m. to 10 
p.m. Friday and Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 * All That Java 
</P>
<P>
 21612 Plano Trabuco Road Trabuco Canyon (714) 459-0800  
</P>
<P>
 Karoke is featured Friday nights, professional singers on Saturday. Available: 
gourmet coffee, custom-blended yogurt and ice cream, soup, shirts and mugs. 
Hours: 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through Thursday, 6 a.m.-11 p.m. Friday through 
Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
 * Truffles 
</P>
<P>
 27772 Vista del Lago Mission Viejo (714) 588-8353  
</P>
<P>
 The store overlooks Mission Viejo Lake and offers live entertainment during 
the summer. Specialty coffee drinks, light lunches, desserts, gourmet food 
gifts, shirts and mugs are available. Hours: 7:30 a.m. to 9 a.m. Monday through 
Friday; 8 a.m. to 10 p.m. Saturday; 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Saddleback Lanes 
</P>
<P>
 25402 Marguerite Parkway Mission Viejo (714) 586-5300  
</P>
<P>
 Practice your delivery on one of 32 bowling lanes. There is a coffee shop and 
a pro-shop. Video games and bowling lessons are available. Hours: 9 a.m. to 1 
a.m. Monday through Thursday; 9 a.m. to 1:30 a.m. Friday through Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Fountain Valley Skating Center 
</P>
<P>
 9105 Recreation Circle Fountain Valley (714) 847-6300  
</P>
<P>
 Regular and in-line skating is offered here as skaters glide to Top 40 music. 
There is a snack bar, video games and pro shop. Group rates available, as are 
birthday and private parties. Sundays are family nights: A family of five can 
get in for $8. Skating hours vary, so call ahead. 
</P>
<P>
 * Ice Capades Chalet 
</P>
<P>
 2701 Harbor Blvd. Costa Mesa (714) 979-8880  
</P>
<P>
 Figure skating and ice hockey lessons are available here, along with public 
skating. There are vending machines if you get the munchies, and video games. 
Public skating times vary each day, so call ahead. 
</P>
<P>
 * The Orange County Market Place 
</P>
<P>
 88 Fair Drive (at Orange County fairgrounds) Costa Mesa (714) 723-6616  
</P>
<P>
 If you're looking for something to on the weekend, try this swap meet. Take 
your time and stroll through booths offering crafts, jewelry, paintings, hair 
supplies, kitchen items, luggage, furniture and toys. Food and drinks also 
available, as are restrooms and an ATM machine (should you find something 
absolutely irresistible). Parking is free. Hours: 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. Saturdays 
and Sundays. 
</P>
<P>
 * Laguna Beach 
</P>
<P>
 This seaside village is fun to stroll through. You'll see art galleries, gift 
shops, cafes, restaurants, clothing stores and the beach, with basketball and 
volley courts. The Laguna Art Museum is at 307 Cliff Drive and is open 11 a.m. 
to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday. Admission is $3 for students. Call (714) 
494-6531. 
</P>
<P>
 * Venice Beach 
</P>
<P>
 A day trip to this fabled beach town up the coast can be fun. You'll find 
street entertainers, Muscle Beach (an outdoor gym) and booths offering food and 
clothes. There are bicycle and roller-skating paths and courts for basketball, 
handball, volleyball and tennis. 
</P>
<P>
 * Angelo's and Vinci's 
</P>
<P>
 Cafe Ristorante 
</P>
<P>
 550 N. Harbor Blvd. Fullerton (714) 879-4022  
</P>
<P>
 Built in the early 1900s, this Italian eatery has developed almost a century's 
worth of personality. As waitress Maria Eugenia says, "There (are) so many 
things to look at, your eyes get tired." Dinners, which include soup, salad, 
bread and butter, run around $9. Maria, who has worked at the restaurant for 13 
years, suggests anything with a creamy basil sauce. A 14-inch cheese pizza, 
which consists of eight slices and easily feeds two people, is $12.95. If you 
have a hankering for Italian around noon, be sure to try the all-you-can-eat 
lunch special Monday through Friday. For $5.50 you get a choice of pastas, 
chicken wings and salad. Hours: 11 a.m. to 7:45 p.m. Sunday through Thursday; 
11 a.m. to 11:45 p.m. Friday and Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Rutabegorz 
</P>
<P>
 211 N. Pomona Fullerton (Locations also in Irvine and Tustin) (714) 871-1632.  
</P>
<P>
 If you're looking for health-conscious food, give Rutabegorz a try. It's hard 
not to be impressed by the wide variety of dishes. Be sure to try one of the 
soups that not only provide "nourishment for the bod, warmth for the soul, joy 
for the spirit," but cost as little as $2.75 a bowl (includes bread). 
Sandwiches range from the simple $2 peanut butter and jelly to the 
Mediterranean Delight for $5.50, which is a pita stuffed with shrimp, artichoke 
hearts, feta cheese and cream cheese. Hours: 11 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. Monday 
through Thursday, 11 a.m. to 11:30 p.m. Friday and Saturday. Closed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Carbon Canyon Park 
</P>
<P>
 4442 Carbon Canyon Road Brea (714) 996-5252  
</P>
<P>
 No matter what age you are, kite-flying is a relaxing pastime that costs next 
to nothing. A stop a Toys R Us can get you a kite for a little as $1.99, 
decorated with everything from the Little Mermaid to World Wrestling Federation 
superstars. How can anyone pass that up? Once you're equipped and the wind is 
just right, visit Carbon Canyon Park. There is a $2 parking fee, but there is 
also adequate air space, plenty of nature trails, a lake with ducks and a 
pretty fun playground. Park is open daily from 7 a.m. to 6 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * Winged Heart Cafe 
</P>
<P>
 136 W. Wilshire Ave. Fullerton (714) 525-1452  
</P>
<P>
 Remember all that funky, mismatched furniture you saw at that garage sale you 
drove by last month? The Winged Heart Cafe probably bought it to create an 
invitingly cozy atmosphere. The cafe is split into three sitting areas, 
including a nonsmoking room. It has has a wide array of dining options, from a 
mini-pizza for $2.25, a bowl of of tomato and basil soup for $2, to chips and 
salsa for $1. Tai iced tea and coffee and "Persian-Armenian-type drinks" are 
unique items. Local talent, whether in the form of poetry, paintings or music, 
is also featured. Music starts around 8:30 p.m., and the performers range from 
fresh young bands such as Hanah's Outfit to regular novelty acts, including 
Rockin' Grandma Blues, a 74-year-old lady who sings/yodels country folk tunes. 
There is an Indonesian music group that the owner describes as "surrealistic, 
dramatic, mind-blowers." The Tap Tones, a tap-dancing trio, is another unique 
act. Hours: 11 a.m. to 2 p.m (lunch) Monday through Friday, 5 p.m. to midnight 
nightly. 
</P>
<P>
 * Regency Coffee Roast 
</P>
<P>
 2500 E. Imperial Highway, Suite 100 Brea (714) 256-9061  
</P>
<P>
 This cafe has about 61 coffee blends and really cool music. It's a a 
patio-oriented cafe, so dress warmly. Tables, chairs and heat lamps are 
scattered about in a little walled area, where you can hear mellow acts such as 
Till Kahrs, a folk and country group, play their hearts out. This is the kind 
of place you could take your mom and still have a good time without worrying 
she'd be shocked by the patrons or the lyrics of one of the bands. Hours: 7:30 
a.m. to 9:30 p.m. Sunday through Thursday, 8 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. Friday through 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Fullerton Museum Center 
</P>
<P>
 301 N. Pomona Ave. Fullerton (714) 738-6545  
</P>
<P>
 With more than 75 of Leo Fender's prototypes, amplifiers and instruments -- 
including the first guitar he ever made -- on display, the Fullerton Museum 
Center has a great exhibit on the late electric guitar pioneer. "Five Decades 
of Fender," which runs through April 2, is great for anyone who enjoys music. 
There is a viewing room where you can watch a tape of the elderly Fender talk 
about his work. TV screens throughout the museum, equipped with headphones, let 
you hear musicians such as Jimi Hendrix and Elvis Costello play Fender guitars. 
In one corner there are four chairs, and next to each is a Fender guitar and an 
amplifier with headphones, where patrons can strum away and make their own 
music. 
</P>
<P>
 With a student ID, a trip to the museum will only cost $1.50. From April 22 
through June 5, the show "Outside/In" will feature drawings, prints, paintings 
and ceramics from artists with developmental disabilities. Hours: noon to 4 
p.m. Wednesday through Sunday; noon to 8 p.m. Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Renaissance 
</P>
<P>
 Brea Marketplace, 955 E. Birch St. Brea (also locations in Laguna & Tustin 
Marketplace) (714) 256-2233  
</P>
<P>
 This cafe has a chic, modern atmosphere with attentive waiters decked out in 
all black. It's great for desserts. Meals are a bit expensive for teens, but 
you can buy appetizers such as chicken skewers for $5.50. Or enjoy a mocha and 
slice of cheesecake while listening to one of the bands that plays there seven 
nights a week. Ask to be put on the mailing list to receive a monthly music 
schedule. Hours: 11 a.m. to 11 p.m. Monday through Thursday; 11 a.m. to 
midnight Friday through Saturday; 9 a.m. through 11 p.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 * AMC Fullerton 10 
</P>
<P>
 1001 S. Lemon St. Fullerton (714) 992-6000 Are you sick of paying $6.75 every 
time you go to the movies at night? With a student ID, you can get into this 
theater for $4.75, the same price as a matinee showing. Twilight shows between 
4 and 6 p.m. are $3.50. Call for show times. 
</P>
<P>
 * Cafe Nove 
</P>
<P>
 3474 E. Orangethorpe Ave. Anaheim (714) 996-2120  
</P>
<P>
 A drink you should try here is is the Funky Monkey, a mocha frappe (slushy) 
with a banana thrown in. Then sit back and enjoy the music. Don't be fooled by 
the sign reading Classical Ballet above the building next to Cafe Nove. It 
serves as an auditorium for funk groups such as Please or Christian bands on 
Sunday nights. There is a $2 to $3 cover to see the bands, but $1 is redeemable 
at the counter in the cafe. Call for the weekly schedule of bands. Hours: 6:30 
p.m. to midnight Monday; 6:30 a.m. to midnight Tuesday through Thursday; 6:30 
p.m. to 1 a.m. Friday; 8:30 p.m. to 1 a.m. Saturday; 9 a.m. to midnight Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
