<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORKS ART GALLERY TO CLOSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ZAN DUBIN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The 5-year-old Works art gallery in the Crystal Court shopping mall will be 
closed by the start of next month, largely because of waning sales, gallery 
director Richard Iri said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Over the past two years, sales have dropped about 40%, Iri said, attributing 
the decline to general economic doldrums and not to the level in Orange County 
of art collectors' sophistication."I think the collectors down here are more 
sophisticated than they're given credit for," he said, "and certainly are 
hungry for seeing both new and established artists." 
</P>
<P>
 There are no plans to reopen the gallery elsewhere in the county, Iri said. 
Owner Mark Moore, who owns a Works Gallery in Santa Monica, has refused to 
discuss the closure. 
</P>
<P>
 An exhibit of work by graduate students from Southern California was to have 
opened in the Costa Mesa gallery next week. "Maybe a mall wasn't the best place 
for the show anyway," said April Ford, one of 17 students to have participated 
in the show. "But I'm sure it would have been good to have (the Works Gallery) 
down there" in Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 The gallery has shown such well-known artists as Kim Abeles, Jay McCafferty, 
Jim Morphesis, Eric Orr, Larry Bell, Tony DeLap and Lita Albuquerque. 
</P>
</TEXT>
